3
00:09.900 --> 00:16.290
This is the second lesson of the series. If you haven't already
watched the first lesson, be sure to check it out.

4
00:16.290 --> 00:23.880
We'll be building directly on what we talked about
in the first lesson, so it's important to have an
understanding of that material going into this lesson.

5
00:23.880 --> 00:30.420
Also, be aware that the series
includes textbook content in addition to videos, and you can find a link
to the textbook content

6
00:30.420 --> 00:35.910
in the video description. This is lesson two of
unit one of the series.

7
00:35.910 --> 00:39.840
Unit one covers the basics
of quantum information.

8
00:39.840 --> 00:46.860
In the previous lesson, we talked about quantum information in the setting of single systems, meaning that we have one
system that stores information

9
00:46.860 --> 00:50.790
and we're describing how
it works in isolation.

10
00:50.790 --> 00:57.930
We spent a fair amount of
time on classical information, mainly to establish a point of reference and to highlight the
mathematical similarities

11
00:57.930 --> 01:02.040
between quantum and classical information.

12
01:02.040 --> 01:09.930
We also saw how quantum states can be represented by vectors, specifically vectors having
complex number entries and Euclidean norm equal to one,

13
01:09.930 --> 01:15.368
and we discussed standard
basis measurements and unitary operations.

14
01:15.368 --> 01:21.540
In this lesson, we're gonna expand our
view to multiple systems, each of which is capable of
storing quantum information.

15
01:21.540 --> 01:27.540
This is not simply a matter of saying that each individual system
works as we discussed last time, there is a sense in which the hole

16
01:27.540 --> 01:34.530
is greater than the sum of the parts, and that's also true of
classical information when probabilities are involved.

17
01:34.530 --> 01:41.790
Multiple systems can
interact with one another and they can be correlated
with one another for instance, and in the quantum setting, this includes the possibility

18
01:41.790 --> 01:46.980
that the systems are entangled, which is a term that you
may have heard about before.

19
01:46.980 --> 01:54.780
Entanglement is a very
important phenomenon in quantum information and we'll have a lot more to say about it as the series continues.

20
01:54.780 --> 02:01.860
There is a simple principle, however, that offers us quite a lot of traction for thinking about and
understanding quantum information for multiple systems,

21
02:01.860 --> 02:08.220
and that is that we can always
take two or more systems and put them together or just conceptually
think about them together

22
02:08.220 --> 02:12.270
and view them as if they form
a single compound system.

23
02:12.270 --> 02:20.430
And when we think about a
compound system like this, as if it's a single system, we recognize that it must be described in a way that's consistent
with everything we learned

24
02:20.430 --> 02:23.970
in the previous lesson on single systems.

25
02:23.970 --> 02:31.620
We'll see how this works
and how the description of quantum information
from multiple systems emerges pretty naturally from how it works for single systems

26
02:31.620 --> 02:39.810
based on this one principle. Here's an overview of the lesson and it happens to be identical to the previous lessons overview,

27
02:39.810 --> 02:45.210
but this time our focus
will be on multiple systems rather than single systems.

28
02:45.210 --> 02:51.810
Just like we did in the previous lesson and for exactly the same reasons, we're going to start with
classical information.

29
02:51.810 --> 02:59.310
Once again, we'll see
very close similarities between the way that quantum
and classical information work at a mathematical level.

30
02:59.310 --> 03:05.580
We won't typically focus so
much on classical information or start each lesson in the series with classical information like this.

31
03:05.580 --> 03:11.910
Subsequent lessons will tend to be focused much more exclusively on quantum information and computation.

32
03:11.910 --> 03:18.120
But here at the beginning
this is a sensible approach and it goes back to the idea that thinking about classical information

33
03:18.120 --> 03:23.220
can serve as a valuable source of guidance for understanding quantum information.

34
03:23.220 --> 03:27.720
We're also gonna discuss
the important concept of a tensor product in
this part of the lesson.

35
03:27.720 --> 03:34.470
Tensor products are critically important in quantum information, but they also arise in
the classical setting.

36
03:34.470 --> 03:41.910
Then we'll move on to quantum information and much like in the previous lesson we'll discuss quantum states,
standard basis measurements,

37
03:41.910 --> 03:46.530
and unitary operations this
time for multiple systems.

38
03:46.530 --> 03:51.210
We'll start by talking
about classical states of multiple systems.

39
03:51.210 --> 03:59.370
Recall from the previous
lesson that a classical state of a system is a
configuration of that system that can be recognized and
described unambiguously

40
03:59.370 --> 04:05.610
without any uncertainty or error. And in mathematical terms, when we refer to a classical state set,

41
04:05.610 --> 04:10.050
we just mean a finite and non-empty set.

42
04:10.050 --> 04:16.530
We'll begin our discussion
of multiple systems by supposing that we have
just two systems X and Y.

43
04:16.530 --> 04:23.070
X has some set of classical states which we'll call sigma just
like in the previous lesson, and y has some set of classical states

44
04:23.070 --> 04:29.280
that we'll call gamma. The set sigma and gamma
could be the same set or they could be different,

45
04:29.280 --> 04:38.580
but we're giving them different names, not only because they
could be different sets, but also because it'll help
us to keep things clear if we give them different names.

46
04:38.580 --> 04:46.290
We'll find that it's
pretty easy to generalize this entire discussion from two systems to any number of systems, but
by starting with two systems,

47
04:46.290 --> 04:52.620
we can focus on the fundamental ideas without getting bogged down in details.

48
04:52.620 --> 05:00.090
Now, imagine that we
put X and Y side by side with X in the left and Y on the right, and we view these two systems together

49
05:00.090 --> 05:03.930
as if they form a single compound system.

50
05:03.930 --> 05:11.280
to give this new system a name, we can write it as an
ordered pair like this, or we can just juxtapose
the two letters like this.

51
05:11.280 --> 05:16.770
These are both common and we
can pick whichever one we want or whichever one is more convenient.

52
05:16.770 --> 05:20.880
Either way, we'll read it as XY.

53
05:20.880 --> 05:29.400
A very natural question
to ask at this point is what are the classical states of this new compound system XY?

54
05:29.400 --> 05:36.030
And the answer to that question is that the classical state set of XY is the Cartesian product of
the two classical state sets,

55
05:36.030 --> 05:40.740
sigma and gamma, which you
can see defined right here.

56
05:40.740 --> 05:47.610
At a given moment, X has some classical state
which is an element of sigma, and Y has some classical state
which is an element of gamma,

57
05:47.610 --> 05:54.150
and we're simply thinking
about these two states together as if they form a single state, and that's precisely the notion

58
05:54.150 --> 06:01.710
that the Cartesian product captures. We have have two elements,
one from each of our sets, and we want to think about
these two elements together

59
06:01.710 --> 06:05.700
as if they form a single
element from a single set.

60
06:05.700 --> 06:11.700
To be clear, there is an assumption here which is that we know
which one of our systems is X and which one is Y,

61
06:11.700 --> 06:18.600
and there's no confusion between them. It's not important that X is physically on the left hand
side and Y is on the right,

62
06:18.600 --> 06:29.970
but rather that the two
systems are distinguishable and that we've decided
to order them this way just so that we can keep
straight which one is which.

63
06:29.970 --> 06:37.710
Here's a very simple example where sigma is the binary alphabet and gamma is the set
containing the four card suits.

64
06:37.710 --> 06:43.800
If X stores a binary value and Y stores one of the four card suits, then there are eight
possible classical states

65
06:43.800 --> 06:50.340
of the pair XY, which you
can see listed right here.

66
06:50.340 --> 06:55.440
For more than two systems, this generalizes in a straightforward way.

67
06:55.440 --> 07:03.270
In particular if X1 through Xn are systems having classical
state sets sigma one through sigma n respectively.

68
07:03.270 --> 07:10.740
Then if we imagine grouping
the n systems together and viewing them as one system, the classical state set is
given by the Cartesian product

69
07:10.740 --> 07:14.490
of the n classical state sets
sigma one through sigma n.

70
07:14.490 --> 07:22.800
As you can see right here on the screen. The Cartesian product
can be defined like this for any number of sets.

71
07:22.800 --> 07:30.300
For example, if we have three systems and they all share the binary alphabet as their classical state set, so in other words we have three bits,

72
07:30.300 --> 07:38.220
then there are eight
possible classical states of the three bits viewed
together as a single system and you can see them listed right here.

73
07:38.220 --> 07:45.330
Each system individually can
be in the state zero or one, and we range over all of
the possible combinations.

74
07:45.330 --> 07:53.190
An n-tuple of classical states can alternatively be written as a string where we drop the
parentheses and the comma like you see right here.

75
07:53.190 --> 07:59.850
And this is particularly sensible when we think about
classical states as symbols as in the very common example
of the binary alphabet

76
07:59.850 --> 08:06.420
that we keep coming back to. Sometimes it's very convenient to do this and it tends to make
our expressions simpler

77
08:06.420 --> 08:13.110
and less cluttered. The notion of a string is in fact formalized
in mathematical terms through carte and products,

78
08:13.110 --> 08:19.140
so this is really just
an alternative notation and not something conceptually different.

79
08:19.140 --> 08:24.690
As an example, let's say that we have
10 bits X1 through X10.

80
08:24.690 --> 08:32.070
That means that the classical state set of the 10 bits together,
which you might naturally think about as a 10 bit register
in a computer for example,

81
08:32.070 --> 08:37.080
is the tenfold Cartesian
product of the binary alphabet with a self.

82
08:37.080 --> 08:43.110
And if we write those states like strings, they look like you see right
here, there's 1,024 of them,

83
08:43.110 --> 08:49.230
so of course they're not all listed here. These three dots right here
are supposed to indicate that there's a pattern that you can deduce

84
08:49.230 --> 08:57.150
and hopefully you get the idea. Now there's a convention
that we're going to follow for ordering the the elements
of Cartesian product sets,

85
08:57.150 --> 09:04.140
and it's important to
clarify this for the sake of representing both probabilistic states and quantum states as vectors.

86
09:04.140 --> 09:12.900
The convention is that
we order the elements of Cartesian product
sets lexicographically, which basically just
means dictionary ordering.

87
09:12.900 --> 09:20.040
To be more specific, we start with the assumption that each of the individual sets that we're taking the Cartesian product of already has its own ordering

88
09:20.040 --> 09:27.180
and we think about a
given n-tuple or a string as if it's a word and we
order them alphabetically.

89
09:27.180 --> 09:34.230
Another way to say this is that the positions within
an n-tuple or a string decrease in significance
from left to right,

90
09:34.230 --> 09:39.210
just like when we write numbers using the digits zero through nine.

91
09:39.210 --> 09:42.270
Here's an example that's
meant to clarify this.

92
09:42.270 --> 09:49.080
If we take the Cartesian product between the sets containing
one, two, and three and the binary alphabet, we get a set containing six elements

93
09:49.080 --> 09:53.010
and here they're listed in the
order that's being described.

94
09:53.010 --> 09:59.850
All of the elements with a
one in the first position come before all of the elements with a two in the first position and they come before all of the elements

95
09:59.850 --> 10:07.080
with a three in the first position. And whenever two elements
agree in the first position, we fall back on the ordering
in the second position.

96
10:07.080 --> 10:11.910
So that's the ordering that
we use for Cartesian products.

97
10:11.910 --> 10:17.850
Notice that when we use this convention and we write n-tuple as strings, we observed some very familiar patterns.

98
10:17.850 --> 10:24.300
For example, the Cartesian product of the
binary alphabet with itself is ordered like you see right here,

99
10:24.300 --> 10:32.280
and you can think about these strings as being ordered numerically if you take these strings
as binary encodings of non-negative mixtures
and this generalizes

100
10:32.280 --> 10:40.050
to any string length. Moving on to probabilistic states, we already know from the previous lesson

101
10:40.050 --> 10:47.010
that a probabilistic state associates a probability with each classical
state of a given system.

102
10:47.010 --> 10:55.200
If we have a compound system where we've taken two or more systems and we're viewing them collectively as if they form a single
system like we just discussed,

103
10:55.200 --> 11:03.360
then a probabilistic state
of this compound system must assign probabilities to the elements of the Cartesian product
of the individual systems,

104
11:03.360 --> 11:11.700
classical state sets. That's because that is
the classical state set of the compound system.

105
11:11.700 --> 11:19.410
For instance, supposing
that X and Y are bits, we have this example of a
probabilistic state of XY.

106
11:19.410 --> 11:28.860
The probability that both
bits are zero is one half and the probability that both
bits are one is one half, and so the two bits never disagree.

107
11:28.860 --> 11:35.490
It's a valid probabilistic state of XY, and we can alternatively
write it as a vector

108
11:35.490 --> 11:45.090
like you see right here and here you can see that we
are following the convention that I described a moment ago for ordering these classical states.

109
11:45.090 --> 11:51.150
This is an example of
a probabilistic state where X and Y are correlated, and this is the sense in which the hole

110
11:51.150 --> 11:57.740
is greater than the sum of the parts. As I suggested before, it's not simply that we
have a probabilistic state

111
11:57.740 --> 12:03.930
of X and a probabilistic state of Y and we put them together, but rather we first put
the systems together

112
12:03.930 --> 12:09.270
and then we think about
probabilistic states of the compound system.

113
12:09.270 --> 12:18.990
To be more precise about
correlations among systems. We start by defining the
notion of independence, which is essentially the
absence of correlation.

114
12:18.990 --> 12:27.090
Here by the way, the term independence refers
to statistical independence as opposed to linear independence
of vectors for instance.

115
12:27.090 --> 12:32.550
It's fundamental notion in
probability and statistics.

116
12:32.550 --> 12:39.990
If we have two systems X and Y and we have some probabilistic
state of XY in mind, then we say that X and Y are independent.

117
12:39.990 --> 12:47.670
If the formula that you
see right here is true for every choice of classical
states a and b of X and Y.

118
12:47.670 --> 12:53.880
One way to interpret this
condition of independence is that it says that the probability for X to be in any one classical state

119
12:53.880 --> 13:00.000
and the probability for Y to be in some other classical state have absolutely nothing
to do with one another.

120
13:00.000 --> 13:08.820
So, learning what state
one of the systems is in doesn't affect the
probabilities associated with the states of the other system.

121
13:08.820 --> 13:15.450
If you imagine randomly choosing
some classical state of X according to some procedure and then randomly choosing
some classical state of Y

122
13:15.450 --> 13:22.110
according to some other procedure that isn't in any way
connected to the one for X, like say if one person flips a coin

123
13:22.110 --> 13:29.940
and another person in a
different room rolls a die, then this is the formula
that you would use to get the probabilities
for different combinations

124
13:29.940 --> 13:39.660
of states to appear. The point of the definition is that independence is
when the formula is valid.

125
13:39.660 --> 13:46.950
When we think about probabilistic states in terms of probability vectors, there's a simple formulation
of this condition

126
13:46.950 --> 13:53.670
specifically if we have a
probabilistic state of XY, which we can express as a
vector in the direct notation

127
13:53.670 --> 14:02.880
as you see right here. Then to say that X and Y are independent is equivalent to the existence
of two probability vectors,

128
14:02.880 --> 14:10.620
cat Phi and cat Psi which by the way we can
simply read as Phi and Psi for the sake of brevity representing

129
14:10.620 --> 14:16.650
probabilistic states of X and Y separately that satisfy this equality
that you see right here.

130
14:16.650 --> 14:24.960
For all choices of a and b, it's essentially a
rephrasing of the definition in terms of vectors.

131
14:24.960 --> 14:31.260
For example, here's a probabilistic
state of a pair of bits XY for which X and Y are independent.

132
14:31.260 --> 14:37.230
The condition that's
required for independence is true for the vectors
that you see right here.

133
14:37.230 --> 14:46.500
That is the probability
for each possible setting for the two bits is given by the product of the corresponding probabilities
for the individual bits.

134
14:46.500 --> 14:54.120
For instance, the probability for both
bits to take the value zero is equal to one sixth, which is equal to one
quarter times two thirds,

135
14:54.120 --> 15:00.300
and likewise for the
other three possibilities which can be checked one at a time.

136
15:00.300 --> 15:08.910
For the probabilistic state we saw earlier on the other hand where we
have two bits that always agree and take the values zero and
one with probability one half

137
15:08.910 --> 15:14.160
we don't have independence and that's why we say that
the bits are correlated.

138
15:14.160 --> 15:19.800
Correlation simply means
a lack of independence.

139
15:19.800 --> 15:25.980
A simple way to argue that the
two bits are not independent is to suppose that they are and to derive a contradiction

140
15:25.980 --> 15:32.880
specifically if the two
bits were independent, there would have to exist
numbers q0, q1, r0 and r1

141
15:32.880 --> 15:39.900
representing probabilities
for the two individual bits so that these equations
right here are satisfied.

142
15:39.900 --> 15:48.330
These are the probabilities
that come from our vector and these are the
equations that must be true by the condition of independence,

143
15:48.330 --> 15:55.440
but if we take a look at this
second equality right here, we see that it demands that
q0 times r1 is equal to zero,

144
15:55.440 --> 16:02.550
but the only way that the
product of two real numbers can possibly be equal to zero is if at least one of those
numbers itself is equal to zero.

145
16:02.550 --> 16:06.960
This is sometimes called
the zero product property of the real numbers.

146
16:06.960 --> 16:12.690
Another way to say it is that the product of two non-zero real
numbers is always non-zero.

147
16:12.690 --> 16:20.070
So this equality right
here implies that either q0 is equal to zero or r1 is equal to zero,

148
16:20.070 --> 16:27.270
but from the first and the last equalities we see that neither of
those two alternatives can possibly be true.

149
16:27.270 --> 16:34.110
If q0 is equal to zero, then this product must equal zero, but it's not equal to zero
and if r1 is equal to zero,

150
16:34.110 --> 16:37.770
then this product must be equal to zero, but that's not true either.

151
16:37.770 --> 16:44.460
So we have a contradiction
and we conclude that X and Y are not independent so they're correlated.

152
16:44.460 --> 16:51.870
The notion of independence
that we just discussed and specifically is formulation in terms of probability
vectors is closely connected

153
16:51.870 --> 16:56.880
to an operation that can
be performed on vectors known as the tensor product.

154
16:56.880 --> 17:03.570
Tensor products can be
defined not only for vectors but also for matrices
and in fact the notion of a tensor product can be defined

155
17:03.570 --> 17:06.780
for many other sorts of
mathematical objects as well.

156
17:06.780 --> 17:15.300
They can be described
in a pretty abstract way that's both important and
useful in pure mathematics, but we can also define
tensor products for vectors

157
17:15.300 --> 17:22.380
in a very simple and concrete way, and that's the path that
we'll take in this lesson.

158
17:22.380 --> 17:31.350
If we have two column vectors Phi and Psi written in the forms that you see here where sigma and gamma are any
choice of classical state sets

159
17:31.350 --> 17:40.260
we like or indices if you prefer, then the tensor product of these vectors is the vector that you see right here.

160
17:40.260 --> 17:47.130
We range over all elements
of the Cartesian product of the two sets, sigma and gamma, and the entry of this
vector that corresponds

161
17:47.130 --> 17:53.460
to each pair ab, which is
written as a string right here, is equal to the product of
the corresponding entries

162
17:53.460 --> 18:03.570
of these two vectors. In other words, the ab entry of Phi tensor Psi is the product of the a entry
of Phi and the b entry of Psi,

163
18:03.570 --> 18:07.620
and that's the meaning of
what's written down here.

164
18:07.620 --> 18:13.770
In essence, this is the same operation that we just saw a few moments ago when we discussed independence

165
18:13.770 --> 18:17.580
and now we're just giving a name to it.

166
18:17.580 --> 18:25.470
Here's exactly the same example
that we saw a moment ago written more explicitly in
terms of the tensor product.

167
18:25.470 --> 18:35.400
Again, we have that one sixth is equal to one quarter times one third, one 12th is equal to one quarter
times one third and so on.

168
18:35.400 --> 18:41.430
Here, by the way are a
couple of alternative ways to write the tensor
product of two vectors.

169
18:41.430 --> 18:48.360
When we're using the direct notation and we write two cats next
to each other like this, it means the tensor product.

170
18:48.360 --> 18:55.230
So you can think about the tensor product as kind of being the default way to multiply to column vectors together.

171
18:55.230 --> 19:02.670
It wouldn't make any sense
to think about a product of column vectors like this in terms of matrix multiplication because the dimensions don't work right,

172
19:02.670 --> 19:06.870
so there's really no concern
about ambiguity here.

173
19:06.870 --> 19:11.555
We can also write the
tensor product like this inside of a cat and it means
exactly the same thing.

174
19:11.555 --> 19:15.450
It's the tensor product
of the two vectors.

175
19:15.450 --> 19:21.990
The first one is very common and in fact it's perhaps more common to write a tensor product like this without the tensor product symbol

176
19:21.990 --> 19:28.800
than it is to include the symbol. The second one is
definitely much less common, but it is sometimes quite helpful mainly

177
19:28.800 --> 19:35.100
as a way to eliminate the need
for additional parentheses in certain situations.

178
19:35.100 --> 19:42.060
We can also express
tensor products explicitly in terms of actual columns of
numbers as you see right here,

179
19:42.060 --> 19:48.090
if we take the tensor product of these two column vectors right here, then this is the vector that we obtain

180
19:48.090 --> 19:53.610
and you can see that the entries here are products of the entries
coming from these two vectors.

181
19:53.610 --> 20:01.170
The ordering of the entries
of the tensor product is consistent with the
definition from a moment ago provided that we follow the convention

182
20:01.170 --> 20:06.000
that I described earlier for ordering the elements
of Cartesian product sets.

183
20:06.000 --> 20:14.970
Following that convention is equivalent to thinking
about the indices of the first vector as
having higher significance than the indices of the second vector,

184
20:14.970 --> 20:23.040
so you can see that as
we go through the entries of the tensor product, we have all of the products involving the first entry of the
first vector on the left,

185
20:23.040 --> 20:32.910
which is alpha one. Then all of the products
involving the second entry of the vector on the left,
which is alpha two and so on.

186
20:32.910 --> 20:41.790
Here's an example where
the vector on the left has three entries and the vector on the
right has four entries so we can see more
clearly what's going on.

187
20:41.790 --> 20:50.100
We have three entries in the first vector, so we start by writing down three copies of the second vector and then we multiply each one of those copies
by the corresponding entry

188
20:50.100 --> 20:54.030
in the first vector like this.

189
20:54.030 --> 21:00.960
We bring the alphas inside like this, and here we're just
multiplying vectors by scalers

190
21:00.960 --> 21:09.480
and finally we remove the
parentheses from the copies and we form a single column
vector like you see right here.

191
21:09.480 --> 21:16.770
As an important aside notice that we have the following formulas for the tensor product of
standard basis vectors.

192
21:16.770 --> 21:23.400
If we take the tensor
product of cat a and cat b, which we can write with
the tensor product symbol or without, as you see here,

193
21:23.400 --> 21:26.760
then the result is simply cat ab.

194
21:26.760 --> 21:34.620
If we want to write ab as an ordered pair rather than a string, we can do that and we obtain
this expression right here,

195
21:34.620 --> 21:41.040
but it's a lot more common
to write this right here where we emit the parenthesis
but we leave the comma.

196
21:41.040 --> 21:49.740
There is a sense in which
this one with the parenthesis is perhaps more correct, but it's a pretty standard
convention in mathematics

197
21:49.740 --> 21:54.030
that parentheses are removed when they aren't necessary or helpful.

198
21:54.030 --> 22:01.650
You can think about them as being implicit in this one right here and it's just less cluttered
and nicer to look at.

199
22:01.650 --> 22:08.490
The tensor product has
an important property which is that it's bilinear and what that means is that it's linear

200
22:08.490 --> 22:13.470
in each of the two arguments provided that the other one is fixed.

201
22:13.470 --> 22:20.250
In a bit more detail it's
linear in the first argument which is expressed by these two equations that you see right here,

202
22:20.250 --> 22:28.410
the first one says that
if we add two vectors, Phi1 and Phi2 and then take
the tensor product with Psi, we get the same result if
we took the tensor product

203
22:28.410 --> 22:31.650
with Psi first and then we added.

204
22:31.650 --> 22:38.100
The second one says that if
we multiply some vector Phi by some scaler alpha and then we take the
tensor product with Psi,

205
22:38.100 --> 22:44.850
the result is the same as if we first took the tensor product of Phi and Psi and then we multiply the result by alpha.

206
22:44.850 --> 22:51.540
And we also have linearity
in the second argument which is the same except that the roles of the two arguments are swapped.

207
22:51.540 --> 23:00.810
This product of bilinear
is pretty straightforward to verify from the definition, but it's good to write it down like this because we'll often make
use of these formulas.

208
23:00.810 --> 23:09.990
Notice by the way that scaler float freely through tensor products in the sense that's expressed by these
qualities that you see right here.

209
23:09.990 --> 23:17.220
That is there's no difference
between multiplying the first argument by a
scaler alpha in this case multiplying the second
argument by that scaler

210
23:17.220 --> 23:21.060
or multiplying the entire
thing by that scaler.

211
23:21.060 --> 23:29.730
These equalities follow from
these two equations right here and because there's no
difference between these vectors, we can just write the
expression as you see right here

212
23:29.730 --> 23:32.760
with no parentheses because
there's no need for them.

213
23:32.760 --> 23:39.540
They're not adding any clarity
or removing any ambiguity, so we just remove them and
we get a cleaner expression.

214
23:39.540 --> 23:43.620
All of this generalizes
to three or more systems.

215
23:43.620 --> 23:50.550
We can define the tensor product
of of three or more vectors by generalizing the formula
for the tensor product of two vectors in the natural way,

216
23:50.550 --> 23:57.480
which you can see expressed right here. Each entry of the tensor product is given by the product of
the corresponding entries

217
23:57.480 --> 24:01.620
of the vectors that we're
taking the tensor product of.

218
24:01.620 --> 24:08.010
An equivalent way to
define the tensor product of three or more vectors
is to do it recursively ultimately falling back on the definition

219
24:08.010 --> 24:16.053
of the tensor product between two vectors. So if n is at least three, we can think about the
tensor product of n vectors

220
24:16.053 --> 24:25.860
Phi1 through Phi n as being the tensor product between whatever vector we get by
taking the tensor product of the first n minus one of
them with the last vector,

221
24:25.860 --> 24:32.910
and if you want to know
what the tensor product of the first n minus one vectors is, you either apply the formula
again in case n minus one

222
24:32.910 --> 24:38.160
is at least three or use the definition
from before if n minus one is equal to two.

223
24:38.160 --> 24:43.440
The two ways of thinking
about tensor products of three or more vectors are equivalent.

224
24:43.440 --> 24:49.680
This time when we have
three or more vectors that we're taking the tensor product of, we don't use the term bilinear,

225
24:49.680 --> 24:52.834
we instead use the term multiline,
but the idea is the same.

226
24:52.834 --> 25:00.390
The tensor product is linear
in each of the positions provided that the vectors in
all of the other positions

227
25:00.390 --> 25:06.960
are fixed. Moving on to measurements
of multiple systems in probabilistic states,

228
25:06.960 --> 25:15.510
we immediately obtain a specification for how measurements
work for multiple systems by simply thinking about them
collectively as single systems

229
25:15.510 --> 25:19.920
provided that all of the
systems are measured.

230
25:19.920 --> 25:26.490
As a simple example, let's suppose that we have two
bits X and Y and collectively they're in this probabilistic
state right here,

231
25:26.490 --> 25:32.550
which we saw before. Naturally, if we measure
both of these bits, we'll get the outcome 00

232
25:32.550 --> 25:39.480
meaning a zero for the first measurement and a zero for the second measurement with probability one half and we'll get the outcome 1,1

233
25:39.480 --> 25:43.620
with probability one half as well. That's quite straightforward.

234
25:43.620 --> 25:49.710
In essence, measuring all of the systems is equivalent to measuring
the entire compound system.

235
25:49.710 --> 25:57.300
If we don't measure all
of the systems however, but instead we just measure
some of the systems, then the situation isn't
quite so immediately clear

236
25:57.300 --> 26:04.200
restricting our attention once again to the case of just two
systems to see the essence of what's going on in as
simple as setting as possible.

237
26:04.200 --> 26:10.740
We can ask the following question, suppose that we have two systems, X and Y that are together as a pair

238
26:10.740 --> 26:14.340
in some particular probabilistic state.

239
26:14.340 --> 26:18.990
What happens if we measure
just X and we do nothing to Y?

240
26:18.990 --> 26:23.340
Well, we can answer this question using some basic probability theory.

241
26:23.340 --> 26:31.680
First, we know that the probability that the measurement
gives a particular outcome has to be given by this formula
that you see right here.

242
26:31.680 --> 26:39.030
We can think about the probabilities for each of the classical
states of the pair XY as if we did measure both and we sum over all the probabilities

243
26:39.030 --> 26:44.010
that are consistent with X being in whatever classical state
a we're interested in.

244
26:44.010 --> 26:48.810
So that's why the sum right here is just over the classical states b of Y.

245
26:48.810 --> 26:55.650
One way to think about this
formula is that the probability of seeing a particular classical
state of X if we measure it

246
26:55.650 --> 27:02.910
has to be consistent with the probability of seeing that state if
we had also measured Y, even though we didn't,

247
27:02.910 --> 27:11.220
that's very natural and intuitive. The probability for a measurement of X to yield a particular outcome can possibly depend on whether or not Y

248
27:11.220 --> 27:14.310
was also measured
irrespective of the outcome.

249
27:14.310 --> 27:23.070
So that tells us what
the probabilities are for the different possible
outcomes of the measurement, but what happens to Y or our
knowledge of Y as a result?

250
27:23.070 --> 27:29.400
The answer is that there still
could exist some uncertainty about the state of Y as a
result of having measured X

251
27:29.400 --> 27:36.720
and seeing a particular result. And that uncertainty is represented by this formula right here for the conditional probability

252
27:36.720 --> 27:42.720
that Y is in some particular
classical state b, given that X is in some classical state,

253
27:42.720 --> 27:47.040
whatever classical state a,
we happen to have measured.

254
27:47.040 --> 27:53.160
To be precise, the probability that Y is
in some classical state b, given that X is in the classical state a,

255
27:53.160 --> 27:59.370
is equal to the probability
that X is in a and Y is in b divided by the probability that X

256
27:59.370 --> 28:02.670
is in the classical state a.

257
28:02.670 --> 28:09.960
So if we measure X, we're going to see
different classical states with probabilities determined
by this formula right here

258
28:09.960 --> 28:17.340
and depending on what outcome we get, we may still have some uncertainty about the classical state of Y and
that uncertainty is reflected

259
28:17.340 --> 28:21.960
by this formula right here.

260
28:21.960 --> 28:28.882
There's actually a very easy
way to rephrase all of this and to perform calculations
for specific cases using the direct notation
and it goes like this.

261
28:28.882 --> 28:36.093
We start by writing down the
probabilistic state of XY as a vector like this, and
this is completely general.

262
28:36.093 --> 28:46.410
The entries are denoted by Pab and these could be any numbers so long as the entire vector
is a probability vector.

263
28:46.410 --> 28:53.640
We can express cat ab as a
tensor product like you see right here and then we can use the
bilinear of the tensor product

264
28:53.640 --> 29:00.300
and specifically the fact that it's linear in the second argument to express this vector
as you see right here.

265
29:00.300 --> 29:07.710
What we're doing is effectively isolating the standard basis vectors
on the left hand side and putting whatever we need
to on the right hand side

266
29:07.710 --> 29:14.370
to allow that because that's gonna reveal what happens when we
measure the first system X.

267
29:14.370 --> 29:23.820
Specifically the probability
to get a particular outcome a is the sum over all of the probabilities that appear in the
parenthesis next to cat a.

268
29:23.820 --> 29:32.130
And conditioned on getting
a particular outcome a, the probability vector that describes whatever uncertainty remains about Y

269
29:32.130 --> 29:35.820
is the vector that was in
the parentheses next to a.

270
29:35.820 --> 29:42.960
Except that we have to normalize it to make it a probability vector and that is is to say that
we have to divide that vector

271
29:42.960 --> 29:47.370
by the sum of the entries in that vector to form a probability vector.

272
29:47.370 --> 29:54.810
Here by the way, the sum is taken overall
c in gamma rather than b just to use a different variable name so that there won't be any confusion

273
29:54.810 --> 29:57.960
about the scope of the
variables if you will.

274
29:57.960 --> 30:05.360
The sums in the numerator
and the denominator should be considered as separate things and we can avoid any chance
of confusion about that

275
30:05.360 --> 30:11.130
by using different
variables for the two sums.

276
30:11.130 --> 30:14.520
Here's a quick example to
illustrate how this all works.

277
30:14.520 --> 30:21.870
Suppose XY is a pair of bits in this probabilistic state right here to understand what happens
when we measure the first bit

278
30:21.870 --> 30:29.250
and we do nothing to the second, we write the vector as you see right here where cat zero and cat
one in the first position

279
30:29.250 --> 30:35.040
are isolated just as we
described a few moments ago.

280
30:35.040 --> 30:43.650
The first possibility is
that the measurement outcome is zero and the probability
of that happening is the sum of the probabilities
inside of the parentheses

281
30:43.650 --> 30:53.910
that are tensored to cat zero. So we get one 12th plus one quarter, which is one third and
conditioned on the outcome zero.

282
30:53.910 --> 31:00.630
The probabilistic state of Y
becomes this vector normalized or equivalently divided by the probability

283
31:00.630 --> 31:06.720
that we just calculated, and so what we get is
this vector right here.

284
31:06.720 --> 31:14.400
The second possibility is that the measurement outcome is one and the calculation is
done in a similar way using the second term in the expression

285
31:14.400 --> 31:26.010
rather than the first term. And if you'd like to verify the details, go ahead as always and pause the video to give yourself a moment do that.

286
31:26.010 --> 31:31.020
You can perform the same
sorts of calculations to figure out what happens when
Y is measured rather than X.

287
31:31.020 --> 31:35.850
It's the same method up to a symmetry between the two systems.

288
31:35.850 --> 31:44.610
This time we write the
probability vector like this, isolating the standard basis vectors on the right like you see right here,

289
31:44.610 --> 31:48.420
but otherwise it works
in exactly the same way.

290
31:48.420 --> 31:52.080
You can also use this method
for more than two systems.

291
31:52.080 --> 32:00.720
It can get a little bit
messy just to write down all of the required expressions, but conceptually it's
exactly the same idea.

292
32:00.720 --> 32:07.050
Finally, for the portion of the lesson
on classical information, we'll take a look at operations
on probabilistic states

293
32:07.050 --> 32:12.420
of multiple systems. Following the same reasoning that we've now seen a couple of times.

294
32:12.420 --> 32:23.190
We conclude that probabilistic operations on multiple systems are just
like probabilistic operations on single systems represented
by stochastic matrices.

295
32:23.190 --> 32:31.440
But this time those matrices
have rows and columns that correspond to the Cartesian product of the individual system's,
classical state sets.

296
32:31.440 --> 32:38.850
That is we're simply
viewing a compound system as if it's a single system and falling back on the description for how probabilistic operations work

297
32:38.850 --> 32:44.250
for single systems from
the previous lesson.

298
32:44.250 --> 32:50.880
Here's an example of an operation called a controlled-NOT
operation on two bits X and Y.

299
32:50.880 --> 32:58.830
This is in fact a deterministic operation and the way that it works is
that if X is equal to one, then a NOT operation is performed on Y

300
32:58.830 --> 33:03.420
and otherwise if X is equal
to zero then nothing happens.

301
33:03.420 --> 33:09.780
The bit X is sometimes
called a control bit because it determines whether
or not the NOT operation is applied to Y

302
33:09.780 --> 33:16.860
and Y is called the target bit because it's the bit that gets acted upon by the NOT operation.

303
33:16.860 --> 33:23.400
You can also imagine
swapping the roles of X and Y so that Y becomes the control
bit and X becomes the target, but that's a different operation

304
33:23.400 --> 33:28.680
from the one that's described here because the operation isn't
symmetric between X and Y.

305
33:28.680 --> 33:36.840
They're both called
controlled-NOT operations, and we just need to specify
which one of the bits is the control bit and
which one is the target bit.

306
33:36.840 --> 33:43.740
This operation has the action
that you see right here on standard basis states and you can check that
action against the definition

307
33:43.740 --> 33:50.520
of the operation. And here is the matrix
representation of the operation.

308
33:50.520 --> 33:57.960
When we think about this operation, we have in mind that there
are these two separate bits and they play the roles that I just described with
X being the control bit

309
33:57.960 --> 34:04.290
and Y being the target bit, but there's really nothing
about this action here or this matrix representation

310
34:04.290 --> 34:08.790
that demands that we
think about these two bits as being separate bits.

311
34:08.790 --> 34:15.630
We could alternatively just
think about this operation as being a deterministic
operation on a system having four classical states

312
34:15.630 --> 34:21.600
that we've decided to name
0,0, 0,1, 1,0 and 1,1.

313
34:21.600 --> 34:28.740
Here's another example of
a probabilistic operation on two bits, which isn't a deterministic
operation this time.

314
34:28.740 --> 34:36.690
The operation sets Y to be equal to X with probability one half and otherwise it goes the other way and it sets X to be equal to Y.

315
34:36.690 --> 34:41.910
This operation doesn't have a special name it's just meant as an example.

316
34:41.910 --> 34:46.410
And here's the matrix
representation of this operation.

317
34:46.410 --> 34:52.770
You can see that it can be expressed as an average of two matrices, one that represents the
deterministic operation

318
34:52.770 --> 34:59.100
where Y is set to whatever
value is stored in X and the other that sets
X to be equal to Y.

319
34:59.100 --> 35:07.470
So here we see that we can take averages of stochastic matrices to obtain new ones just like we had in the previous lesson.

320
35:07.470 --> 35:14.100
Now, let's consider
the following question. Suppose that we have two
probabilistic operations each on its own system

321
35:14.100 --> 35:20.370
described as usual by stochastic
matrices and to be precise, let's suppose that M is
a probabilistic operation

322
35:20.370 --> 35:25.770
on a system X and N is a
probabilistic operation on a system Y.

323
35:25.770 --> 35:32.910
The question is if we
simultaneously perform M on X and N on Y, how do we ascribe
the effect that this has

324
35:32.910 --> 35:36.510
on the compound system XY?

325
35:36.510 --> 35:42.990
Thinking about about this
intuitively for a moment, if we simultaneously
perform the two operations on their own respective systems,

326
35:42.990 --> 35:50.700
then we are in fact
performing an operation on the compound system, so it should be described
by some stochastic matrix.

327
35:50.700 --> 35:57.930
The short answer to this
question is that the matrix is obtained by taking a tensor product, not between vectors like
we talked about earlier,

328
35:57.930 --> 36:02.610
but between matrices in this
case, the matrices M and N.

329
36:02.610 --> 36:09.180
So let's take a few moments
to discuss tensor products of matrices and then we'll
return to this question.

330
36:09.180 --> 36:16.470
Here's the definition
of the tensor product between matrices and
it's very much analogous to the tensor product between vectors.

331
36:16.470 --> 36:25.710
If we suppose that the two
matrices that we're working with are written in the forms that you see here so that the entries of M are
denoted alpha ab as a and b

332
36:25.710 --> 36:31.975
range over some classical state set sigma and the entries of N are
denoted by beta cd as c and d

333
36:31.975 --> 36:35.910
range over some classical state set gamma.

334
36:35.910 --> 36:41.790
Then the product of M and N is the matrix that you see right here.

335
36:41.790 --> 36:45.570
What we have is similar
to the tensor product between vectors.

336
36:45.570 --> 36:53.400
the rows and columns of M tensor N correspond to pairs of classical states which are written as strings right here,

337
36:53.400 --> 36:58.110
and the entries are products of the corresponding entries of M and N.

338
36:58.110 --> 37:03.360
Here's another way of writing it in terms of the individual
entries of these matrices.

339
37:03.360 --> 37:12.570
The ac bd entry of M tensor N is the product of the ab entry
of M and the cd entry of N.

340
37:12.570 --> 37:20.340
There's another way of
describing M tensor N, which is that it's the
unique matrix that transforms any vector of the form Phi tensor Psi

341
37:20.340 --> 37:26.940
into the tensor product of M applied to Phi with and applied to Psi, and that has to be true for every choice

342
37:26.940 --> 37:30.300
of these vectors Phi and Psi.

343
37:30.300 --> 37:37.680
One way to think about
this is that the tensor product of matrices gets along perfectly with the tensor product between vectors.

344
37:37.680 --> 37:43.500
This is an equation that you
would naturally hope is true and indeed it is.

345
37:43.500 --> 37:49.800
In terms of matrices that
are written out explicitly, we can define the tensor
product as you see here.

346
37:49.800 --> 37:57.540
There's a lot of dots in this equation and they're meant to
illustrate the pattern, which is the same pattern
that we had for vectors except now we have rows and columns

347
37:57.540 --> 38:00.930
as opposed to just column vectors.

348
38:00.930 --> 38:04.110
In case it's not clear, the
following example may help.

349
38:04.110 --> 38:09.000
Here we're talking about
the tensor product of two two by two matrices.

350
38:09.000 --> 38:16.740
We first write down four
copies of the second matrix, one for each entry of the first matrix.

351
38:16.740 --> 38:23.040
We multiply each of these
copies of the second matrix by the corresponding
entry of the first matrix,

352
38:23.040 --> 38:30.660
and then we collect it all into
a single four by four matrix as you see right here.

353
38:30.660 --> 38:38.310
We can also define the
tensor product of three or more matrices in an analogous way and perhaps the easiest
way to express this

354
38:38.310 --> 38:48.930
is as you see right here
where we have a formula for each entry of the tensor product, which is simply the product
of the corresponding entries.

355
38:48.930 --> 38:58.500
You can also define the tensor product of three or more matrices recursively in terms of the tensor
product of just two matrices just like we had for vectors.

356
38:58.500 --> 39:05.640
And one final note is
that the tensor product of matrices is multiplicative, which means that a
product of tensor products

357
39:05.640 --> 39:09.150
is equal to the tensor
product of the products.

358
39:09.150 --> 39:15.150
You can think about
this as a generalization of the formula from a few moments ago for the action of intensive
product of matrices

359
39:15.150 --> 39:22.230
on tensor product of vectors. And again, this is something that we
would certainly hope to be true and we can be glad that it is

360
39:22.230 --> 39:26.160
and we'll make use of this
fact whenever we need.

361
39:26.160 --> 39:33.150
And now we can return to
the question from before which asks how we describe
the effect of performing an operation M on a system X

362
39:33.150 --> 39:40.249
and an operation N on the system Y together as an operation
on the compound system XY.

363
39:40.249 --> 39:45.960
And the answer to that
question is that the action is described by the
tensor product of M and N.

364
39:45.960 --> 39:53.820
Tensor products represent independence this time between operations as opposed to what we saw
before for probability vectors.

365
39:53.820 --> 40:01.110
Here's a quick example. Suppose that we perform
the probabilistic operation described by this matrix on a bit X.

366
40:01.110 --> 40:09.150
This happens to be an operation
that we saw in lesson one and we simultaneously perform
a NOT operation on a bit Y.

367
40:09.150 --> 40:16.740
The combined operation on the pair XY is therefore represented by the tensor product of the matrices corresponding to these two operations.

368
40:16.740 --> 40:23.430
Here's the one on X and
here's the NOT operation on Y and we get this matrix
that you see right here.

369
40:23.430 --> 40:28.080
And you can see that indeed
this is a stochastic matrix and that will always be the case.

370
40:28.080 --> 40:36.840
The tensor product of any
two stochastic matrices or any number of stochastic
matrices for that matter will always be stochastic.

371
40:36.840 --> 40:45.360
It is a very common situation
that we encounter a situation in which one operation is
performed on one system and nothing is done to another system.

372
40:45.360 --> 40:55.050
In this situation, we follow exactly the same prescription with the understanding that doing nothing is represented by the identity matrix.

373
40:55.050 --> 41:01.200
For example, if we have two bits X and
Y and we reset the bit X to the zero state, which is the same thing

374
41:01.200 --> 41:09.270
as performing the constant
zero function on X and we do nothing to Y, then the resulting operation on the par XY

375
41:09.270 --> 41:12.600
is represented by this
tensor product right here.

376
41:12.600 --> 41:20.670
All of this generalizes
to any number of systems and we'll see some additional examples when we turn to the quantum setting, which works in exactly the same way

377
41:20.670 --> 41:28.560
except that we have unitary matrices rather than stochastic matrices, and that's enough about
classical information for now.

378
41:28.560 --> 41:33.480
Now we'll turn our attention
to quantum information and how it works for multiple systems.

379
41:33.480 --> 41:37.050
The pattern is the same as it
was for classical information.

380
41:37.050 --> 41:43.440
We can view multiple quantum systems as single compound systems and apply what we know
from the previous lesson.

381
41:43.440 --> 41:50.700
Again, tensor products
will play a key role and overall we obtain a description for how quantum information
works for multiple systems.

382
41:50.700 --> 41:57.270
That's very much analogous
and mathematically similar to what we just saw for
classical information.

383
41:57.270 --> 42:00.570
We'll start with quantum states.

384
42:00.570 --> 42:08.070
Quantum states of multiple systems are represented by column vectors having complex number entries
and Euclid arm equal to one

385
42:08.070 --> 42:11.640
just like quantum states
of single systems.

386
42:11.640 --> 42:19.620
This time the indices of
the quantum state vectors correspond to the Cartesian product of the classical state sets
of the individual systems

387
42:19.620 --> 42:25.800
because again, that is
the classical state set of the compound system.

388
42:25.800 --> 42:34.530
For example, if X and Y or Qubits, then the classical state
set for the par XY together is the Cartesian product of the
binary alphabet with itself,

389
42:34.530 --> 42:39.210
which we can think about as
the set up all binary strings of length two.

390
42:39.210 --> 42:46.470
So these vectors that you see here are all examples of quantum
state vectors of XY.

391
42:46.470 --> 42:53.160
If we want to, we can alternatively write
these vectors like this where we have a separate
cat for each Qubit

392
42:53.160 --> 42:57.330
where the tensor product
between them is implicit.

393
42:57.330 --> 43:02.460
Or we can also write the
tensor product symbol explicitly like this if you prefer.

394
43:02.460 --> 43:09.180
And another option is
to subscript the cats with the names of the systems
that they represent like this.

395
43:09.180 --> 43:13.110
And you can do this with
the tensor product symbol or without.

396
43:13.110 --> 43:19.470
That can sometimes be very helpful for keeping things straight.

397
43:19.470 --> 43:27.090
These are just different styles for expressing the same vectors and we can pick whichever one we want or whichever we prefer or
whichever makes the most sense

398
43:27.090 --> 43:34.890
for the situation at hand. When things get more
complicated for instance, we might decide that one of
these styles adds clarity

399
43:34.890 --> 43:39.420
and we're free to make
whichever choice we want.

400
43:39.420 --> 43:44.520
Tensor products of quantum state vectors are also quantum state vectors.

401
43:44.520 --> 43:52.800
For the case of two systems for instance, if Phi is a quantum state
vector of a system X and Psi is a quantum state
vector of a system Y,

402
43:52.800 --> 43:58.530
then the tensor product of Phi and Psi is a quantum state vector of XY.

403
43:58.530 --> 44:08.340
We call states like this product states and similar to what we saw in the classical probabilistic setting, they represent independence
between the systems X and Y.

404
44:08.340 --> 44:16.860
So for instance, if one person has a laboratory
in one part of the world and they create a system X and initialize it to the quorum state Phi

405
44:16.860 --> 44:23.340
and another person in
another part of the world independently initializes a system Y to the quantum state Psi,

406
44:23.340 --> 44:29.670
then if we choose to think about XY as forming a single system even though it's two parts or in different parts of the world,

407
44:29.670 --> 44:35.730
then the compound system XY is
in the state Phi tensor Psi.

408
44:35.730 --> 44:40.050
This all generalizes to
more than two systems in the natural way.

409
44:40.050 --> 44:47.670
If we have quantum
states Psi1 through PsiN of separate systems Xn through Xn, then the tensor product of these n vectors

410
44:47.670 --> 44:56.940
represents a quantum state, which is again called a product state of the compound system X1 through Xn.

411
44:56.940 --> 45:00.420
Here's an example of a
quantum state of two Qubits.

412
45:00.420 --> 45:08.520
Although it might not
look like it immediately. It is an example of a product state because we can write
it as a tensor product as you see right here.

413
45:08.520 --> 45:19.560
So it's an example of a
product state regardless of how it's written, what's relevant is whether
or not it's possible to write it as a tensor product.

414
45:19.560 --> 45:24.870
This quantum state, however, which is again a state of two
Qubits is not a product state.

415
45:24.870 --> 45:30.900
It's similar in spirit to
the example that we saw in the probabilistic setting of two perfectly correlated random bits

416
45:30.900 --> 45:35.760
and the same argument reveals that it can't be written
as a tensor product.

417
45:35.760 --> 45:41.220
So let's move this over here and let's take a look at the argument in a little bit more detail.

418
45:41.220 --> 45:47.850
Let's imagine that we
could write this state as a tensor product of
two vectors Phi and Psi.

419
45:47.850 --> 45:55.260
The entry corresponding
to the classical state 0,1 is zero for this vector, which we can see just by looking at it.

420
45:55.260 --> 46:02.550
This would imply however, if the vector was a tensor
product of two vectors that the zero entry of Phi
times the one entry of Psi

421
46:02.550 --> 46:09.240
would be equal to zero, but that means that either
the zero entry of Phi or the one entry of Psi is equal to zero

422
46:09.240 --> 46:16.530
or they both could be equal to zero, but that contradicts the fact
that these two products here must both be non-zero.

423
46:16.530 --> 46:23.340
They're equal to one
of our squared of two. The argument is in fact pretty
much identical to what we had in the probabilistic setting.

424
46:23.340 --> 46:26.520
There's nothing uniquely
quantum about this at all.

425
46:26.520 --> 46:31.980
In any case, what we find is that the original state is not a product state.

426
46:31.980 --> 46:35.970
Notice that it's not important
that these two numbers here are one over squared of two.

427
46:35.970 --> 46:40.680
All that matters is that
both values are non-zero.

428
46:40.680 --> 46:47.370
This particular quantum state
is a very interesting one. It's an example of an
entangled state of two Qubits.

429
46:47.370 --> 46:50.760
We'll talk more about
entanglement later in the series.

430
46:50.760 --> 46:57.870
Entanglement can be complicated, particularly when we're
talking about quantum states in the general formulation
of quantum information,

431
46:57.870 --> 47:04.410
but here in the simplified description of quantum information entanglement is equivalent to a lack of independence.

432
47:04.410 --> 47:11.580
So for a quantum state vector,
if it's not a product state, it's an entangled state
and this particular state

433
47:11.580 --> 47:17.010
is commonly viewed as
the archetypal example of an entangled quantum state.

434
47:17.010 --> 47:24.210
And in fact, we sometimes
think about this state as representing one unit of entanglement, particularly when we're
thinking about entanglement

435
47:24.210 --> 47:28.410
as a resource that can be
used to do interesting things.

436
47:28.410 --> 47:35.760
The quantum state that
we just talked about is one of the four so-called bell states, which you can see here
along with the names

437
47:35.760 --> 47:42.240
that are commonly used for these states, Phi plus, Phi minus,
Psi plus and Psi minus.

438
47:42.240 --> 47:48.960
They're all entangled
and they do form a basis for the space of all
vectors representing states of two Qubits.

439
47:48.960 --> 47:53.940
So these four vectors together
are called the Bell basis.

440
47:53.940 --> 48:00.830
It's a very commonly
encountered collection of quantum states named
in honor of John Bell, who was a physicist who made
very important contributions

441
48:00.830 --> 48:04.110
to the study of entanglement in the 1960s.

442
48:04.110 --> 48:09.420
Here are a couple of well known examples of quantum states of three Qubits.

443
48:09.420 --> 48:12.600
The first one is called a GHZ state.

444
48:12.600 --> 48:18.780
It's kind of like the Phi
plus state that we just saw except for three Qubits instead of two.

445
48:18.780 --> 48:25.590
And the second example is called a W state and it looks like you see here, so it's uniform over
the three binary strings

446
48:25.590 --> 48:29.730
of length three that have
exactly one bit set to one.

447
48:29.730 --> 48:38.640
Neither of these states is a product state and they both have interesting properties and arise pretty commonly as examples, so they're good to know about
and we will see them again.

448
48:38.640 --> 48:44.520
Next we'll talk about
measurements of systems in quantum states.

449
48:44.520 --> 48:50.670
Following the same reasoning
that we've been following this far in the lesson, which is to think about multiple systems

450
48:50.670 --> 48:58.260
as if they're single systems. We immediately arrive at a description for how measurements of
multiple quantum systems work

451
48:58.260 --> 49:03.690
provided that all of the
systems are measured.

452
49:03.690 --> 49:10.400
That is if we have some
quantum state vector Psi that represents a quantum
state of an n-tuple systems

453
49:10.400 --> 49:16.740
X1 through Xn and we measure
the entire compound system, which is equivalent to measuring

454
49:16.740 --> 49:24.330
every one of the individual systems, then each possible n-tuple
of classical states will be the outcome of the measurement

455
49:24.330 --> 49:33.720
with probability equal to
the absolute value squared of the entry of Psi that
corresponds to that n-tuple.

456
49:33.720 --> 49:40.890
For example, if we have
a pair of systems XY in this quantum state right here, then if we measure both systems,

457
49:40.890 --> 49:47.190
then we'll get the outcome zero hearts meaning zero for the measurement of X and hearts for the measurement of Y

458
49:47.190 --> 49:54.750
with probability nine 25ths and we'll get the outcome one
speeds with probability 16/25.

459
49:54.750 --> 50:04.500
That's really quite straightforward. We're essentially just ignoring the fact that these are two separate systems and we're viewing them as if
they're one single system,

460
50:04.500 --> 50:10.410
but this raises the
following natural question, which we already considered
in the classical setting.

461
50:10.410 --> 50:18.540
Suppose that we have two systems X and Y that are collectively
in some quantum state and we don't measure both, but
we only measure one system.

462
50:18.540 --> 50:22.740
Let's say that we measure the system X and we do nothing to Y.

463
50:22.740 --> 50:29.850
Of course, we can also ask what happens if we measure Y and not
X and more generally what happens if we have
three or more systems

464
50:29.850 --> 50:38.400
and we measure some proper subset of them. But once we have an
answer to this question, we'll have answers to
those questions as well.

465
50:38.400 --> 50:46.620
We know that in general
a quantum state vector of the pair XY takes the
form that you see right here, assuming as usual that sigma and gamma

466
50:46.620 --> 50:51.120
are the classical state sets
of X and Y respectively.

467
50:51.120 --> 50:57.120
The entries of this vector are
denoted by alpha ab ranging over all the possible choices of a and b,

468
50:57.120 --> 51:03.270
and they can be any complex number that cause this vector
to be a unit vector.

469
51:03.270 --> 51:09.360
Now we already know that if
both systems are measured, then we get the probabilities for the different possible outcomes

470
51:09.360 --> 51:14.520
by taking the absolute value squared of the corresponding entry.

471
51:14.520 --> 51:22.500
And so if just X is measured, then the probability to
obtain a particular outcome a is given by this expression,

472
51:22.500 --> 51:29.880
we simply some over all of
the possible outcomes b, that could be obtained
if Y was also measured even though it wasn't.

473
51:29.880 --> 51:33.480
The idea is the same as in
the probabilistic setting.

474
51:33.480 --> 51:40.740
The probability to get
a particular outcome when X is measured can't
possibly depend upon whether or not Y was also measured.

475
51:40.740 --> 51:46.290
So this tells us what
the probabilities are for the different possible outcomes.

476
51:46.290 --> 51:54.330
In addition, there will be some
change in the state of Y as a result of having
performed this measurement on X and having obtained a particular outcome.

477
51:54.330 --> 51:57.630
So let's take a look at how this works.

478
51:57.630 --> 52:04.740
Similar to what we did in
the probabilistic setting, we can express the
quantum state vector Psi as you see right here

479
52:04.740 --> 52:11.100
where Phi a is this vector for each choice of a classical state a of the system X,

480
52:11.100 --> 52:15.090
we're using the bilinear
of the tensor product just like before.

481
52:15.090 --> 52:22.110
Only now we've chosen to name
these different vectors Phi a, just for convenience.

482
52:22.110 --> 52:29.190
We already observed that the probability that the measurement yields
each possible outcome a is as you see right here,

483
52:29.190 --> 52:36.600
but now we can see that this probability is equal to the Euclid norm
squared of the vector Phi a,

484
52:36.600 --> 52:43.980
and now as a result of the measurement of X giving a particular outcome a, we have that the quantum state
of the compound system XY

485
52:43.980 --> 52:47.430
becomes this state that
you see right here.

486
52:47.430 --> 52:54.060
Just like we had for single systems, the state collapses in essence, but it doesn't collapse
entirely in general,

487
52:54.060 --> 53:01.260
it only collapses as far as it needs to in order to be consistent
with the measurement of X yielding the outcome a.

488
53:01.260 --> 53:07.980
The quantum state of Y becomes Phi a normalized meaning that we
divide by its Euclid norm

489
53:07.980 --> 53:15.240
so that it becomes a unit vector. This is analogous to what happened in the
probabilistic setting where instead of dividing
by the Euclid norm,

490
53:15.240 --> 53:20.610
we divided by the sum
of the entries of Phi a in order to get a probability vector.

491
53:20.610 --> 53:28.680
But here because we're
talking about quantum states, we divide by the Euclid norm
to get a quantum state vector.

492
53:28.680 --> 53:34.530
Let's take a look at a couple of examples to see how this works
for a specific state.

493
53:34.530 --> 53:41.340
Here's the state that we'll consider. We're assuming that X and Y are Qubits and they're in this particular state Psi.

494
53:41.340 --> 53:44.790
And let's suppose that X is measured.

495
53:44.790 --> 53:51.750
We begin by writing the state's
Psi as you see right here, effectively isolating the
standard basis factors of X

496
53:51.750 --> 53:55.920
and tensing them with whatever we need to in order to get the original state.

497
53:55.920 --> 54:01.440
Just like in the general
description from a moment ago.

498
54:01.440 --> 54:07.050
The probability to obtain the outcome zero is the Euclid norm squared
of this vector right here.

499
54:07.050 --> 54:11.490
The thing that we're tensing to cat zero in our expression of the vector Psi.

500
54:11.490 --> 54:18.210
And so the probability is three quarters and conditioned on
getting the outcome zero.

501
54:18.210 --> 54:24.960
The quantum state of
the pair XY becomes this where we normalize the
vector tensor to cat zero,

502
54:24.960 --> 54:30.870
and that's equivalent to
dividing by the square root of the probability that
we just calculated.

503
54:30.870 --> 54:37.980
We can then simplify
and this is what we get.

504
54:37.980 --> 54:42.660
The probability to get the
measurement outcome one is calculated in a similar way.

505
54:42.660 --> 54:49.830
We take the Euclid arm squared
of this vector right here. The thing that's tensed to cat
one in our expression of Psi

506
54:49.830 --> 54:58.260
and the resulting
probability is one quarter, which it has to be of course, because our probabilities
have to sum to one.

507
54:58.260 --> 55:05.970
In this case, the quantum state of XY becomes this where again we're normalizing by dividing by the Euclid norm

508
55:05.970 --> 55:11.550
so that we obtain this quantum
state vector as a result.

509
55:11.550 --> 55:16.950
The same method is used
in a symmetric way, if Y is measured instead of X.

510
55:16.950 --> 55:23.940
Here's the original quantum state vector, and this time because Y
is measured instead of X,

511
55:23.940 --> 55:30.330
we express the vector Psi
as you see right here, where this time we isolate the
standard basis vectors of Y

512
55:30.330 --> 55:37.620
rather than X tensing
with whatever we need to to get an expression of Psi.

513
55:37.620 --> 55:41.640
Going through the calculation, which you can check by
pausing the video if you like.

514
55:41.640 --> 55:47.670
We see that the probability
to get the outcome zero is Phi8 this time, and here's
the quantum state vector

515
55:47.670 --> 55:53.940
that results conditioned
upon getting that result.

516
55:53.940 --> 56:01.230
And the probability to get the
outcome one is three eights, in which case this is
our quantum state vector.

517
56:01.230 --> 56:07.110
You can use exactly the same method in case you have more than two systems and any proper subset
of them are measured.

518
56:07.110 --> 56:13.110
And there's an example
in the textbook content for this lesson that you can
check out if you're interested.

519
56:13.110 --> 56:20.550
In short, we can always divide the systems into two separate collections, the ones that are measured
and the ones that aren't.

520
56:20.550 --> 56:29.040
And once we've done that, we fall back on the method
method that I've just described, and that's how measurements for multiple quantum systems work.

521
56:29.040 --> 56:35.430
And now finally, we move on to unitary
operations on multiple systems.

522
56:35.430 --> 56:41.070
Using the same basic idea that multiple systems can be viewed as single compound systems.

523
56:41.070 --> 56:49.230
We conclude what you see
written here on the screen, quantum operations on compound systems are represented by unitary matrices

524
56:49.230 --> 56:56.850
just like we have for single systems and specifically the rows and columns of those unitary matrices correspond to the Cartesian product

525
56:56.850 --> 57:03.630
of the classical state sets of whatever collection of
systems we're talking about.

526
57:03.630 --> 57:10.080
For example, if we have a system X
whose classical states are one, two, and three and Y is a Qubit,

527
57:10.080 --> 57:18.600
then the matrix that you see right here is an example of a unitary matrix that represents an
operation on the pair XY.

528
57:18.600 --> 57:28.020
The details of how we
order Cartesian products that we talked about before don't really matter for
the sake of this example, it's just a six by six matrix
that happens to be unitary.

529
57:28.020 --> 57:32.910
There's nothing special about it, although it is built out of a
couple of important matrices.

530
57:32.910 --> 57:41.250
The point is that you could
choose any six by six unitary matrix and it would represent
a unitary operation on XY.

531
57:41.250 --> 57:47.850
If we apply a collection of
unitary operations independently each on its own system, then the action of them all together

532
57:47.850 --> 57:52.920
on the compound system is
given by the tensor product.

533
57:52.920 --> 57:57.150
And here on the screen you can see a more precise
statement of that fact.

534
57:57.150 --> 58:04.020
If our unitary operations are described by the unitary matrices U1 through Un one for each of our systems,

535
58:04.020 --> 58:11.580
then the combined action
on the compound system is given by the tensor
product of U1 up to Un.

536
58:11.580 --> 58:19.080
Once again, similar to what we had in the probabilistic setting, an important example is that
we apply some unitary operation

537
58:19.080 --> 58:23.670
U to a system X and we do
nothing to some other system Y.

538
58:23.670 --> 58:28.710
The operation on XY that we get is U tensored with the identity matrix.

539
58:28.710 --> 58:32.070
The identity matrix
describes doing nothing to Y.

540
58:32.070 --> 58:40.200
Sometimes it's helpful to write explicitly that this identity matrix
corresponds to the system Y, just to make the formulas more clear.

541
58:40.200 --> 58:47.640
And one option is to
give the identity matrix a subscript like this that indicates the system that it acts upon.

542
58:47.640 --> 58:55.050
When it's clear enough, though we usually don't
bother with a subscript, but when things get more complicated, it can be very helpful.

543
58:55.050 --> 59:02.760
And we can also consider
the symmetric case where some unitary
operation V is applied to Y and nothing is done to X,

544
59:02.760 --> 59:08.910
and this time the resulting
unitary operation on XY, is represented by this
tensor product here.

545
59:08.910 --> 59:15.990
And once again, we can put a subscript on the
identity matrix if it helps.

546
59:15.990 --> 59:19.590
Here are a couple of specific examples.

547
59:19.590 --> 59:29.970
If X and Y are Qubits and we
perform a Hadamard operation on X and we do nothing to Y, we get the matrix that you see right here.

548
59:29.970 --> 59:37.770
If on the other hand, we perform the Hadamard operation on Y and we do nothing to X, the ordering of the tensor
product is reversed.

549
59:37.770 --> 59:41.910
And so we get the matrix
that you see right here.

550
59:41.910 --> 59:47.160
Not every unitary operation
on a compound system can be expressed as a tensor product.

551
59:47.160 --> 59:50.940
If we have a tensor product,
then we have independence.

552
59:50.940 --> 59:58.560
And there are some pretty
fundamental examples of operations that certainly
don't act independently on multiple systems.

553
59:58.560 --> 60:04.740
For example, if X and Y have
the same classical state set, which could be any
classical state set sigma,

554
60:04.740 --> 60:09.060
then we can think about the
swap operation on the pair XY.

555
60:09.060 --> 60:17.490
This operation doesn't change the ordering of the two systems, we still have X in the
left and Y on the right, but rather it represents
swapping the contents

556
60:17.490 --> 60:27.270
of the two systems. Here you can see that expressed
in the form of an equation where we have a tensor
product of two quantum states.

557
60:27.270 --> 60:31.860
Another way to write it is as
a matrix as we see right here.

558
60:31.860 --> 60:37.560
The way you can think
about this description is that it tells you what happens for standard basis vectors.

559
60:37.560 --> 60:43.830
And once we know what happens
for standard basis vectors, we know what happens for
arbitrary quantum states by linearity,

560
60:43.830 --> 60:47.490
which in fact is also true for
this expression right here.

561
60:47.490 --> 60:56.520
So this particular operation right here happens to be a deterministic operation as well as a unitary operation.

562
60:56.520 --> 61:02.970
If X and Y are Qubits, for instance, we get this matrix
representation right here.

563
61:02.970 --> 61:10.680
Here's an interesting connection
between the swap operation and the four Bell states, which are shown right
here for convenience.

564
61:10.680 --> 61:17.010
The swap operation leaves the
first three of them alone, but it puts a minus sign in
front of the Psi minus state,

565
61:17.010 --> 61:20.250
so there's something
special about that one.

566
61:20.250 --> 61:27.450
You can check these equations directly by looking at these vectors and considering what happens
for the standard basis states

567
61:27.450 --> 61:33.030
swapping the two classical states for the first three Bell
states doesn't do anything we get the same state we started with.

568
61:33.030 --> 61:40.260
In the fourth case however, the minus sign effectively
moves from one term to the other when we perform the swap of the classical states,

569
61:40.260 --> 61:43.770
and that's equivalent to multiplying the vector by minus one.

570
61:43.770 --> 61:50.220
So performing the swap operation somehow kicks out a minus sign
from this fourth Bell state.

571
61:50.220 --> 61:58.890
We'll have more to say about
these equations later on, but now let's move on to
another type of operation, which is a controlled operation.

572
61:58.890 --> 62:05.070
We're going to suppose that X is a Qubit and Y is any system you want.

573
62:05.070 --> 62:12.840
If U as a unitary operation on Y, then a controlled U operation on XY is the operation that's
expressed right here.

574
62:12.840 --> 62:20.250
First, using the direct notation and then using what's
called a block matrix you just imagined filling
in this bigger matrix

575
62:20.250 --> 62:25.530
with the smaller ones where these zeros really represent matrices
filled with zeros.

576
62:25.530 --> 62:34.230
So each of these four blocks represents a matrix having a number
of rows and columns that agrees with the number
of classical states of Y.

577
62:34.230 --> 62:40.590
The idea of a controlled operation, which we already encountered
in the classical setting when we discussed a
controlled NOT operation,

578
62:40.590 --> 62:44.730
is that if X is set to zero,
then nothing happens to Y.

579
62:44.730 --> 62:48.390
But if X is set to one,
then U is applied to Y.

580
62:48.390 --> 62:56.730
So X is called the control Qubit, and Y is called the target system, which in general doesn't
have to be a Qubit.

581
62:56.730 --> 63:01.590
For a specific example,
which I just mentioned, we have a controlled NOT operation.

582
63:01.590 --> 63:08.070
If the first qubit is set
to zero, nothing happens. And if the first qubit is set to one, then a NOT operation or equivalently,

583
63:08.070 --> 63:11.700
a sigma X operation is
applied to the second Qubit.

584
63:11.700 --> 63:15.960
And here is it's matrix representation.

585
63:15.960 --> 63:23.040
We're talking about two Qubits here, so we could equally well
decide that the second Qubit is the control and the
first is the target.

586
63:23.040 --> 63:33.630
To describe that operation, we just swap the ordering
in the tensor product, and the result is the matrix
that you see right here.

587
63:33.630 --> 63:39.240
If instead of a controlled-NOT operation, we consider a controlled sigma
Z or controlled Z operation.

588
63:39.240 --> 63:45.720
We obtain this matrix
representation right here. And for this one, it doesn't actually matter
which is the control and which is the target.

589
63:45.720 --> 63:49.440
We get the same result either way.

590
63:49.440 --> 63:52.920
We can go further and we can consider a controlled swap operation.

591
63:52.920 --> 63:59.400
And here we're talking
about swapping two Qubits, so we end up with three Qubits when we include the controlled Qubit.

592
63:59.400 --> 64:02.940
Each matrix representation
looks like this.

593
64:02.940 --> 64:08.700
It's pretty special operation and it's known as a Fredkin operation, or more commonly a Fredkin gate.

594
64:08.700 --> 64:15.150
When we think about it
as a gate in a circuit, we'll discuss circuits in the next lesson.

595
64:15.150 --> 64:21.630
The last example is a controlled,
controlled-NOT operation, which again is an
operation on three Qubits.

596
64:21.630 --> 64:28.830
And here's its matrix representation. This operation is much better
known as a Toffli operation or a Toffoli gate.

597
64:28.830 --> 64:37.590
We'll discuss it further
and we'll see why both it and the Fredkin can operation are very important
operations in a later lesson.

598
64:37.590 --> 64:45.000
And that is the end of the second lesson. In this lesson, we discussed how quantum information works for multiple systems.

599
64:45.000 --> 64:50.400
I hope you'll join me for
the third lesson soon, which is on quantum circuits
protocols and games.

600
64:50.400 --> 64:51.303
Bye until then.
